      <hedline>
        <hl1>In Defense of a Sonata</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David H Porter letter about May 20 article on pianist Sviatoslav Richter defends Beethoven's Opus 54 Piano Sonata (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Soviet Pianist Who Wasn't All Thunder'' [May 20]:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Soviet Pianist Who Wasn't All Thunder'' [May 20]:</p>
        <p>I enjoyed Bernard Holland's article on Sviatoslav Richter but protest his characterization of Beethoven's Opus 54 Sonata. It may be less frequently performed, but it is scarcely ''the black sheep of the Beethoven sonatas,'' let alone ''forgotten for good reason,'' as Mr. Holland writes. In the hands of a Richter or an Alfred Brendel this sonata is magical, a worthy companion to its more familiar neighbors, the ''Waldstein'' and ''Appassionata,'' and filled with fascinating anticipations of the late sonatas: in a word, pace Holland, unforgettable.</p>
        <p>David H. Porter  Saratoga Springs, N.Y.</p>
        <p>SVIATOSLAV RICHTER</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
